NEW: Made the new bounds optional and only on success.

tf.repeat generates Where op with compile constant input. This should be constant folded so that the use of the output in Gather op generates correct shaped output. Which, then later goes through the Reshape op.

The relevant IR looks something like this,

%gather_indices = tf.Where(%mask)
%elements = tf.GatherV2(input, %gather_indices)
%result = tf.Reshape(%elements, %shape)

[{"sha":"d23458fdd2655c83ff9d54725062ded31b644ba4","author":{"email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com","name":"George Karpenkov"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] Do not check that the size of the XLA parameter buffer is exactly equal to the size of the underlying given buffer

Instead, check that the underlying allocation is "large enough". This is also
more consistent with XLA:GPU behavior.

The mismatch can happen when the input comes from tf.where, which is backed by
an allocation larger than is actually required.

Providing tests is a bit of a chicken-and-an-egg problem: this is tested in
where ops tests, which are disabled due to this issue.
